[[File:Mohrs zout.JPG|right|thumb|350px|[[Mohr's salt]], ammonium iron(II) sulfate, {{chem|(NH|4|)|2|Fe(SO|4|)|2}}]]
'''Double salts''' are salts containing more than one [[ion|cation]] or [[ion|anion]], and are obtained by combination of two different salts which were [[crystallization|crystallized]] in the same regular ionic [[lattice (order)|lattice]]. Examples of double salts include [[alum]]s (with the general formula M<sup>I</sup>M<sup>III</sup>[SO<sub>4</sub>]<sub>2</sub>·12H<sub>2</sub>O) or [[Tutton's salt]]s (with the general formula [M<sup>I</sup>]<sub>2</sub>M<sup>II</sup>[SO<sub>4</sub>]<sub>2</sub>·6H<sub>2</sub>O).<ref name=InorgChem>{{Housecroft3rd}}</ref> Other examples include [[potassium sodium tartrate]], [[ammonium iron(II) sulfate]] (Mohr's salt), and [[Alstonite|bromlite]]. [[Aluminium sulfacetate]], {{chem|Al|2|SO|4|(CH|3|CO|2|)|4}}, is an example of a double salt with two distinct anions; another is the salt {{chem|Tl|4|(OH)|2|CO|3|}} where hydroxyl-centred triangles of thallium, {{chem|[Tl|3|(OH)]|2+}}, are a recurring structural motif.<ref>{{cite journal|title = Hydroxocentered {{chem|[(OH)Tl|3|]|2+}} triangle as a building unit in thallium compounds: synthesis and crystal structure of {{chem|Tl|4|(OH)|2|CO|3}}|first1 = Oleg I.|last1 = Siidra|first2 = Sergey N.|last2 = Britvin|first3 = Sergey V.|last3 = Krivovichev|journal = [[Zeitschrift für Kristallographie]]|volume = 224|issue = 12|pages = 563–567|doi = 10.1524/zkri.2009.1213|year = 2009|bibcode = 2009ZK....224..563S}}</ref>

Double salts should not be confused with [[coordination complex|complexes]]. When dissolved in water, a double salt completely dissociates into simple ions while a complex does not; the [[coordination complex|complex ion]] remains unchanged. For example, KCeF<sub>4</sub> is a double salt and gives K<sup>+</sup>, Ce<sup>3+</sup> and F<sup>&minus;</sup> ions when dissolved in water, whereas K<sub>4</sub>[YbI<sub>6</sub>] is a complex salt and contains the discrete [YbI<sub>6</sub>]<sup>4&minus;</sup> ion which remains intact in [[aqueous solution]]s.<ref name=InorgChem/> It is therefore important to indicate the [[coordination complex|complex ion]] by adding square brackets "[ ]" around it.  Double salts are distinct from mixed-crystal systems where two salts co-crystallise;<ref>{{cite journal|title = Mixed crystals and double salts between metal(II) salt hydrates|last = Balarew|first = Christo|journal = [[Zeitschrift für Kristallographie]]|volume = 181|issue = 1-4|pages = 35–82|doi = 10.1524/zkri.1987.181.1-4.35|year = 1987|bibcode = 1987ZK....181...35B}}</ref> according to an [[Ida Freund]] publication from 1904 reprinted in 2014, the former involves a chemical combination with fixed composition, whereas the latter is a mixture.<ref>{{cite book|url = https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9ttkAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA448|title = The Study of Chemical Composition: An Account of its Method and Historical Development with Illustrative Quotations|first = Ida|last = Freund|authorlink = Ida Freund|publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]|year = 2014|isbn = 9781107690301|chapter = Mitscherlich and the Connection between Crystalline Form and Chemical Composition|pages = 385–453}}</ref>

In general, the properties of the double salt formed will not be the same as the properties of its component single salts.

